Database migrations (Alembic)
=============================

Alembic manages the **Postgres** schema for the app's SQLModel tables. The database URL and the
target metadata come from the app itself — see `env.py`:

- URL is built from `settings` (`POSTGRES_*`), the same one `DatabaseFactory` uses.
- `target_metadata = SQLModel.metadata`, with every model imported via
  `src/app/core/db/models_registry.py` so autogenerate sees the full schema.
- Tables owned by other libraries at runtime (the LangGraph checkpointer `checkpoints*`, and mem0's
  `mem0migrations` / `longterm_memory`) are excluded from autogenerate by `_include_name` in
  `env.py` — never let a migration drop them.

Common commands (or use the `make` targets)
--------------------------------------------

    make migrate                      # alembic upgrade head  (apply pending migrations)
    make migration m="add X to Y"     # autogenerate a new migration — then REVIEW it
    make migrate-down                 # alembic downgrade -1
    make migrate-stamp                # alembic stamp head  (see "Fresh databases" below)

Always review an autogenerated migration before committing: autogenerate can surface unrelated
pre-existing drift and emits `NOT NULL` columns without a `server_default` (unsafe on a populated
table). Trim it to the intended change and add server defaults where needed.

Relationship with `create_all`
------------------------------

The app still calls `SQLModel.metadata.create_all` at startup, and the test suite uses it against
an in-memory SQLite DB — that stays the bootstrap for a brand-new database and for tests.
`create_all` only ever CREATES missing tables; it never ALTERs an existing one, so **schema changes
to existing tables must go through an Alembic migration.**

- Existing database (tables already present): `make migrate`.
- Fresh database (the app just create_all'd the full current schema): `make migrate-stamp` to mark
  it at head without re-running migrations — running `migrate` there would fail trying to add
  columns that `create_all` already created.
